By Sergey Sazhin
Every student who lived in the former Soviet Union is familiar with the practice of spending his summer vacation working in a collective farm. Every student in the Soviet Union had to work one summer month without pay, just for food and bed. It is good that nowadays such practice has become obsolete. A lot of incidents happened then, students losing not only valuables but also their health, including intoxication with fertilizers and insect repellents, let alone attacks perpetrated against them by locals.
In 1981, I was studying in the Tobolsk Ichthyology College. Tobolsk is an old Siberian
town known for the tombs of the Decembrists — participants in the unsuccessful conspiracy to overthrow Czar Nicholas I in December 1825. A famous Russian chemist, Dmitri Mendeleev, inventor of the periodic table of the elements in 1869, was also a resident of this town.  Our group was inducted to do agricultural work for one month. Our working place was in little village. I cannot even remember its name — it is so small and among so many of them and besides, that happened over a quarter of a century ago. We reached it by truck at night jumping through the bumpy road. Of course, we did not expect luxury accommodations. We all slept in one collective, long, shelf-like bed. To relieve our bodily functions we had to walk from the hut to share with 30 other guys a little, freezing outhouse. We worked long, long hours, 10 to 12 hours a day in the field. Our group of 30 students and one teacher loaded potatoes on trucks. After a while our arms looked like those of a monkey’s. Yet, we were young and full of energy and, despite exhaustion, we call for relaxation. We played guitar and sang songs, horsed around and did a lot of silly things (knotting somebody’s towel, night chorus in the nearby forest, wild dances in local club).  One may say that out life was not that bad. Yet other circumstances made it tough, like the food. We had instead of real butter only bad-quality margarine and other cheap food. Every one of us sometimes fell victim to stomach problems one way or another and we often rushed to take a shit in our freezing little outhouse. After a week the outhouse was a sty and the stench was so unbearable that we had to take a shit any place
around in the field that soon resembled a minefield. Guys had to be very careful where
they step. Nobody dared to do that at night.  One of my hobbies is judo. I found among my friends a worthy opponent, Gavrilo Spiridonov.

Gavrilo is an old Russian name. He looked like a Russian hero painted by Viktor Vasnecov.  Sometimes we fought with him, using our sleeping quarters for arena. None of us has any advantage over the other. We fought like growling, snarling, nasty bears. The group was roaring and rooting for their favorite guy.
I decided to beat him in order to attract the fancy of a girl I liked a lot, Lena Markitanova,
the leader of the Young Communists Association. She had a gorgeous, slender body and every guy in the group had the hots for her.  I hold Gavrilo by his chest and tried lift him up from the floor. I interpreted Lena’s
flirting eyes as an invitation for lovemaking and I doubled my efforts. Gavrilo made a mistake and I used that chance to throw him on the floor. It was too much
of an effort for me.
Gavrilo’s voice faded after I farted louder than a bull. On top of that I pissed in my pants
and dirtied my pants. Did not get the medal, but I got everybody’s laughs.
However, after many years, what I remember the most was Lena’s enticing, laughing
eyes.  I am in the left of picture. Gavrilo is in the center of group. We are on the truck.
p.s. Behind year we went to town Troizk for summer practical work with Lena. There  is
huge  fisher Nursery Company  there. We have a short  love during several nights. After  that she still cold and begun hunts  for men who can marry with her. I waited a military recruitment and was not a good candidate for marriage.

Students in track. I am left.
